[center][b]Congratulations! You have advanced (alot of) Inspecting level(s)! You have now reached level 50![/b][/center]

Now that you have advanced your inspecting level, you are now ready fo intermediate inspecting. We're getting a little advanced, so bare with me if you don't get something.

Let's take this:

[code]
public void replaceitem(int oldID, int newID) {

for(int i2 = 0; i2 < playerItems.length; i2++)
{
if(playerItems[i2] == oldID+1)
{
int newamount = playerItemsN[i2];
deleteItem(oldID, getItemSlot(oldID), playerItemsN[i2]);
addItem(newID, newamount);
}
}
}
[/code]

This code is more harder than the other two codes you faced earlier. However, if you stare at it for a moment, you'll notice it's quite easy. 

[b]Get smart![/b]

You should know [b]if(playerItems[i2] == oldID+1)[/b] Is getting the old ID (it's getting ready to make a new item). Also, you should know [b]int newamount = playerItemsN[i2];[/b] Is making a new item (by refreshing amount). [b]deleteItem(oldID, getItemSlot(oldID), playerItemsN[i2]);[/b] and [b]addItem(newID, newamount);[/b] are also common sense because those are the same things you use for adding starters or deleting a players item. You can also notice, oldID which is mentioned above is that same oldID and newID which is also mentioned above is that same newID.

[b]Exercise[/b]

Try this:

[code]
